88–Deceased","1190":"1190","1230":"1230","abt 1240":"about 1240","1240":"1240","1196":"1196","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","Abt 1212":"about 1212","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1288":"1288","1188":"1188","about 1224":"about 1224","about 1245":"about 1245","1328":"1328","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Llechryd, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llechryd, Cardiganshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","Acron, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gwladys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old form of   Gladys  , of uncertain derivation."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]},{"name":"Morgan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Welsh Morcant , traditionally a boy's name. In Britain since the late 1990s the name has become equally popular as a girl's name, perhaps adopted with conscious reference to  King Arthur's  jealous stepsister  Morgan le Fay . Elsewhere in the English-speaking world, especially in North America, where it also enjoys considerable popularity, it is used predominantly for girls."],"variants":[{"name":"Morcant","meanings":["Traditional: composed of an unexplained first element + a second representing the Old Celtic element <i>cant</i> ‘circle; completion’."]}]},{"name":"Fychan","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Avan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"Wallia","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Lars, Erik, Berger, Alrik, Alvar, Anders, Astrid, Halvar, Hilmer, Ingegerd, Iver, Johan.","Swedish: variant of   Vallin  . Compare   Wahlin   and   Wallen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walin","meanings":["‘Newborn baby’.  Al-Walīd ibn-‘Abd-al-Malik  (  d. 715 ) was the Umayyad caliph (  705–15 ) whose armies conquered Spain and attempted to capture Constantinople."]},{"name":"Vallin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Jesus, Juan, Rafael, Angel, Cirilo, Delfina, Enrique, Esperansa, Esteban, Francisco.","Asturian-Leonese (<b>Vallín</b>): habitational name from any of the places in Asturias (Spain) named Vallín, from a diminutive 